sec.p:
Our finding of a higher likelihood of feeding in the presence of a parakeet within the parakeet range compared with sites outside, suggests habituation to parakeets following prior exposure. This is particularly evident considering the overall lower mean total number of visits in the sites within the parakeet range compared with those outside. Without data on individual behavior, it is not possible to distinguish whether this effect is due to an increased number of visits by bold individuals who have become accustomed to the parakeets, comparable to behavior seen in several other bird species exposed to a predator (
  Quinn and Cresswell 2005; 
  van Oers 2005; 
  Minderman et al. 2010; 
  Rockwell et al. 2012), but see 
  Couchoux and Cresswell (2011); or, if the perception of risk lowers for all individuals with continued exposure (
  Ellenberg et al. 2009; 
  Rodríguez-Prieto et al. 2011). The former would suggest that some individuals may be disproportionately impacted by nonnative species’ presence, whereas the latter would indicate population-wide adjustment to the presence of a nonnative species, and potentially lower overall impact.
